00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:21.000
<v BERNSTEIN>
My dear young friends:	I am happy and

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:24.000
proud to welcome you to our tenth season 

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:26.000
of Young People's Concerts. Imagine, it's 

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:29.000
been a whole decade we've been playing 

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:32.000
and talking about music for you. I 

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:33.000
don't know how much you've actually 

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:36.000
learned, but I like to think we must be 

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.000
doing something right, because -- well 

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:42.000
because it's our tenth season. And to add 

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:44.000
to the festivities, this is also the 

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:46.000
first season in which all our programs 

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:49.000
will be seen on television in color. 

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:52.000
That's why I've got this wildly 

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
colorful tie on. Which brings us to 

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:59.999
our subject: what is a mode? Well, for one 

00:01:59.999 --> 00:02:02.000
thing, modes have nothing to do 

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:05.000
with neckties, or dresses, or even with 

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:08.000
fashions of a musical kind. Modes are 

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:11.000
simply scales — though not perhaps those 

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:13.000
scales you are forced to practice on your piano.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:15.000
They are rather special scales ;*and I

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:16.000
wouldn't have dreamed of bothering you 

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:19.000
with them, except for an incident that 

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:22.000
happened a few months ago. My 14-year old 

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:24.000
daughter Jamie happened to ask me one 

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:26.000
day why a certain Beatles song had such 

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:28.000
funny harmony; she couldn't seem to find 

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:30.000
the right chords for it on her guitar.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:33.000
I began to explain to her that the song 

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:36.000
was modal — that is, based on what 

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:38.000
is called a mode: I went on to show 

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:40.000
her the chords that come from it--

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:42.000
and she got so excited she wanted to 

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:44.000
know more and more about it, until finally 

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:47.000
she saids "Why not tell all this on 

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:49.000
a Young People's Program? Nobody ever heard 

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:53.000
of modes!" Well, I thought, Jamie is just a 

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:55.000
natural music-lover with the usual 

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:57.000
weekly piano lesson, and if she finds 

00:02:57.000 --> 00:02:59.000
this material fascinating, why shouldn't 

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:02.000
you? So here goes, and you can blame it 

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:07.000
all on Jamie. O.K. We already know that a

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:11.000
mode is a scale.* But what, first of all, is 

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:13.000
a scale? I'm sure you know; but maybe 

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:15.000
you've never tried to put it into words.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:18.000
A scale is simply a way of dividing 

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:22.000
up the distance between any note and the

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:25.000
same note repeated an octave higher 

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:28.000
The most famous and often used division 

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:30.000
of this octave in our Western 

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:31.000
music 

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:35.000
is what we call the major scale. I guess

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:37.000
you all know that one. And the other 

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:42.000
famous one is the minor scale. I guess 

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:43.000
you know that too. Now what's the 

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:45.000
difference between the major and the 

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:47.000
minor? Many people think the only 

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:49.000
difference is that the major scales are 

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:52.000
happy-sounding, and the minor ones are sad. Well, 

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:55.000
that's sometimes true, but not always. The 

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:57.000
real difference is in the arrangement of 

00:03:57.000 --> 00:03:59.999
the intervals — you remember how deeply we 

00:03:59.999 --> 00:04:03.000
dug into intervals last season? And you 

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:05.000
remember we found that the smallest 

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:07.000
interval - that is, the shortest distance from one 

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:10.000
note to its nearest neighbor—is called a 

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:16.000
half-tone (we called it a "minor second" last year, but never mind that now.) So from C to C# is a step 

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.000
of a half-tone. And from C# to D is 

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.000
again a half-tone.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:27.000
But from C straight to D is a 

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:29.000
whole tone — 2 halves make a whole. 

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:33.000
Get it? Fine. Now this entire C-major 

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:36.000
scale is just a series of whole 

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:38.000
tones and half-tones arranged in a 

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:42.000
special order:* C to D, a whole tone; D to E again a whole tone; 

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:44.000
E to F, a half-tone (since we've skipped nothing); then 3 whole 

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:47.000
tones: F to G, G to A, A to B; and finally B to C, a half-tone. 

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:48.000
That's the formula for any major scale, whether it begins on C or on Eb or on Q-sharp; 2 whole tones, a half-tone, 3 whole tones, and a half-tone.*

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:50.000
Now the minor scale is almost the same 

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:52.000
arrangement of intervals: the main 

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:54.000
difference being in the third note of 

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:57.000
the scale which in the minor is a half

00:04:57.000 --> 00:04:59.999
-tone lower so that the minor scale

00:04:59.999 --> 00:05:03.000
sounds like this 

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.000
And it doesn't matter whether you start 

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:07.000
on C or on Eb or Q sharp:

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:08.000
OR (WITHOUT CUT) - SKIPPED
Again, it doesn't matter what note you
start with:	

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:10.000
you can always get a (major or) minor 

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:12.000
scale by following the proper 

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:15.000
arrangement of intervals that

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:30.000
SKIPPED
* a whole-tone, a half-tone, 4 whole-tones,
and a half-tone. But let's not burden
CUT	ourselves with any more formulas: *
the important thing is that those two
kinds of scales, major and minor, are
modes.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:34.000
But they are only two modes out of a 

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:43.000
much larger number of possible ones.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:46.000
Now before I tell you anything else 

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:48.000
about modes, we are going to play you a 

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:51.000
short but marvelous piece, by the great

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:54.000
French composer Debussy, which is 

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
completely based on modes that are 

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:00.000
neither major nor minor. This brilliant 

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:03.000
piece, which is called Festivals, or, in 

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:06.000
French, Fetes, uses all kinds of modes 

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:08.000
which, of course, you won't know about yet; 

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:11.000
you'll just be hearing beautiful sounds 

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:13.000
that will seem a bit strange and ear-

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:15.000
tickling. But we're goirg; to play it 

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:16.000
again later, toward the end of this program, 

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:20.000
and I'm sure that by then you'll be able 

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:22.000
to recognize all the peculiar things that are 

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:25.000
going on. So, for the moment, just 

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:27.000
imagine a splendid 

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:30.000
night-time celebration, with many-colored 

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:32.000
lights and lanterns everywhere, 

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:34.000
gorgeous fireworks in the sky, and 

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:37.000
everyone dancing in costumes of 

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:40.000
long ago. Suddenly, in the middle of 

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:42.000
the piece, the music breaks off, and 

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:45.000
a procession is heard in the far 

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:48.000
distance. This march-like music gets 

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:50.000
nearer and nearer, and when it 

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:53.000
arrives in all its glory, the dance-music 

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:55.000
and the march music are heard together 

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:58.000
in an excitirg blend of tumultuous 

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.000
sounds. Finally 

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
it grows late, the crowds thin-out--as 

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:05.000
does the music--and it all ends in a 

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:07.000
whisper, with an echo or two of the 

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:09.000
night's festivities hanging in the silent air. 

00:07:09.000 --> 00:11:36.000
Here is Debussy's Fetes.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:04.000
How about that for an exciting piece?

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:08.000
It's positively goose-fleshy. And a 

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:09.000
lot of the excitement comes from 

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:12.000
the fact that it uses those strange 

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:15.000
scales, or modes. 

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:18.000
For instance, right at the 

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:19.000
beginning, the driving rhythm 

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:20.000
SKIPPED
of those bright, shining open fifths way up high 
 
tell us that this music is neither major nor minor. Those empty fifths 
 
contain in them neither the 3rd note of the major scale , 
which would make them into major chords , nor the 3rd note of the minor scale , which would make them minor chords . They're just empty, neutral.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:20.000
Now, underneath them, appears that first swirling dance-

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:27.000
tune which sounds at first like

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:31.000
the usual minor mode. In fact,

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:34.000
the first 5 notes are exactly the

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:36.000
first five notes of the minor scale but 

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:42.000
then comes the twist. Those notes don't

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:44.000
belong to any minor scale we know.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:45.000
SKIPPED
That  is where it gets peculiar.
But Debussy's tune is shaped just like 
a scale, isn't it? . 

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:49.000
So what scale is it? Answer: It's the 

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:52.000
scale of the Dorian mode. Now don't let 

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:55.000
that throw you: keep calm, sit back and 

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:57.000
let's quietly find out just what this 

00:13:57.000 --> 00:13:59.999
Dorian mode is, and why it sounds so 

00:13:59.999 --> 00:14:03.000
special. The word Dorian obviously comes 

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:06.000
from the Greek: and in fact the Dorian mode, as well as 

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.000
the others we're about to 

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.000
discover, does come originally 

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:13.000
from the music of ancient Greece. We don't 

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:14.000
know too much about that old Greek music: 

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:17.000
what we do know is that the Greek modes 

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:19.000
eventually made their way to Rome, and 

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:21.000
were taken up by the Roman Catholic 

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:23.000
Church during the middle ages in a 

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:26.000
somewhat different form. But the church 

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.000
kept the old Greek names for the modes:	

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:32.000
Dorian, Phrygian, Lydian, Mixolydian, 

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:34.000
Aeolian, Locrian, and Ionian. There's 

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.000
a mouthful for you. But they're 

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.000
much easier to understand than their 

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:41.000
names are to pronounce. They are 

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:42.000
still used today in certain Catholic churches 

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.000
all over the world, in those beautiful 

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:48.000
chants called plain-song. Here is a tiny 

00:14:48.000 --> 00:15:08.000
example of plain-song, in the Dorian mode:

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:26.000
That is music in the Dorian 

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:29.000
mode, u exactly the same scale, the 

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:31.000
same arrangement of intervals, as Debussy used 

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:34.000
in his Fetes. But what is the scale? Ah, 

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:37.000
that's easy. To find the Dorian mode on 

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:40.000
your piano, all you have to do is to start 

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:43.000
on the note D.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:46.000
and play only white notes all the way up to the next D. 

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:49.000
and you've got it. Isn't that simple? And that's true

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:51.000
of all the other Church modes as well -- 

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:53.000
they're all to be found by 

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:54.000
starting on a given white note and 

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:57.000
making a scale u white notes only. 

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:00.000
Isn't that lucky? And we're luckier 

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:03.000
still with the Dorian mode, because it 

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:05.000
starts on D, and D is the first letter of

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:08.000
the word Dorian! So you have no excuse 

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:10.000
for forgetting how to find this mode:

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.000
Dorian, 

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:15.000
Capital letter D, the note D, white notes all the way 

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:18.000
up--and there it is.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:21.000
Now here's another piece in the Dorian 

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:30.000
mode -- I wonder if you know it:

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:56.000
Along comes Mary, in the ancient and 

00:16:56.000 --> 00:17:00.000
honorable Dorian mode -- the same mode we 

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:03.000
just heard in Debussy and in the plain-

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:05.000
chant. Who'd have thunk it? What is 

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:08.000
that old Greek mode doing in today's pop 

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:10.000
music? Well, I'll tell you. From about the 

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:13.000
time of Bach until the beginning of our 

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:16.000
own century -- roughly 200 years — our 

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:18.000
western music has been based almost 

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:21.000
exclusively on only two modes -- the major 

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:23.000
and the minor. I can't go into the why's 

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:25.000
and wherefore's now, but it's true.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:28.000
And since most of the music we hear in 

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:30.000
concerts today was written during that 

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:33.000
200 year period, we get to think that 

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:34.000
major and minor modes are all there are. 

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:37.000
But the history of music is much longer 

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:39.000
than a mere 200 years. There was a 

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:41.000
lot of music sung and played before Bach, 

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:44.000
u all kinds of other modes. And in

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:46.000
the music of our own century, when 

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:49.000
composers have gotten tired of being 

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:51.000
stuck with major and minor modes all the time, 

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:53.000
there has been a big revival of those 

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:56.000
old pre-Bach modes. That's why Debussy 

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.000
used them so much, and other modern 

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:01.000
composers like Hindemith and Stravinsky, 

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:03.000
and almost all the young song writers of

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:06.000
today's exciting pop music.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:08.000
The modes have provided them with a fresh 

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:11.000
sound, a relief from that old, overused 

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:12.000
major and minor. 

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:15.000
If that swinging opening of 

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:17.000
Along Comes Mary had been written in the 

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:19.000
usual, every-day minor mode, it would sound 

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:22.000
like this.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:25.000
Sort of square, isn't it? Ordinary. But 

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:31.000
this -- this has a kick in it, and the kick 

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:37.000
is Dorian. You can see that this Dorian

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:39.000
mode is almost like our ordinary minor 

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:42.000
mode, but not quite. And that not quite 

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:43.000
makes a big difference; and that 

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:46.000
difference gives the music a certain 

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:49.000
ancient, primitive, almost oriental feeling. 

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:51.000
That's why the plain-chant we heard 

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:54.000
before is so stirring, so ancient as to 

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:57.000
seem timeless. And that's why the tune 

00:18:57.000 --> 00:18:59.999
in Debussy's Fetes seems so exotic, and 

00:18:59.999 --> 00:19:02.000
of another age. And that's why Along 

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:05.000
Comes Mary sounds so primitive, and earthy. 

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:08.000
Now listen to this 

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:11.000
opening section of Sibelius' Sixth 

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:13.000
Symphony, which is also in the Dorian 

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:15.000
mode, and see if you feel again that 

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:19.000
same timeless, brooding, ancient, far-off 

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:22.000
quality, this time coming from the 

00:19:22.000 --> 00:20:09.000
remote, lonely forests of Finland:

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:12.000
Do you see what I mean by the special 

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:14.000
feeling of the Dorian mode? 

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:18.000
Let's get technical for a 

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:19.000
minute, and find out just what it is that 

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:24.000
gives us this feeling. As we know, this 

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:28.000
Dorian mode is practically like our 

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:29.000
usual minor mode — with one very big

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:32.000
differences the 7th 

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:34.000
note of the scale 

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:37.000
That 7th note is called the "leading tone," because it 

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:39.000
is supposed to lead us back to the keynote, or tonic 


00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:43.000
which is D. And that leading tone leads

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:45.000
us back to the tonic by the smallest interval possible, a half-tone.

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:03.000
But in the Dorian mode,

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:08.000
there's a full whole-

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:13.000
tone between the leading-tone and the tonic. 

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:26.000
Do you feel how strange and modal that is? 

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:31.000
The minute we hear that 

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:33.000
we feel behind it the weight of many 

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:36.000
centuries, of a different, older, more 

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:39.000
Eastern culture. Bach never wrote an Amen 

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:41.000
like that, and neither did Beethoven or 

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:44.000
Brahms. But in our own century it gets 

