Well, that's an awful 

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:01.000
lot about the Dorian mode - which, you will 

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:03.000
never forget as long as you live, starts 

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:07.000
on D. Dorian - D. Now let's get on to the next 

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:10.000
one - which starts on E - 

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:12.000
the Phrygian mode. Again, 

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:14.000
this is terribly easy to find on the 

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:17.000
piano:	you start on E, again play

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:19.000
only white notes up to the next E. 

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:22.000
and there's your Phrygian mode.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:25.000
Now this Phrygian mode is very much like 

00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:28.000
the Dorian:	it is a minor mode 

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:32.000
and it has that lowered 7th leading 

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:37.000
tone 

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:39.000
But it also has something 

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:42.000
else very unusual:	it is the only mode

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:46.000
that begins with a step of a half-tone--

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:48.000
that is, from the first note, E, to the 

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:51.000
second, F, is a mere half-step.

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:53.000
And that gives the mode a specially sad 

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:58.000
quality which can be heard in so much

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:02.000
Spanish and Hebrew and gypsy music. 

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:04.000
For instance, you all know the beginning 

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:06.000
of Liszt's 2nd Hungarian 

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:10.000
Rhapsody -- don't you? 

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:17.000
Do you hear that typical sad, gypsy sound?


00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:20.000
That's the Phrygian mode for you. It's a 

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:23.000
very oriental-sounding one, and has 

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:26.000
been much used by Western composers 

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:28.000
