piercing note that seems to come from a 

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:02.000
far-away place. And that's only natural:

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:04.000
These modes do come from far-away — 

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:07.000
the Middle-East, and Eastern 

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:10.000
European countries like Greece, Bulgaria, 

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:13.000
Finland, Russia, and Poland. In fact, Poland is 

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:15.000
one of the main breeding-grounds for 

00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:18.000
this Lydian mode. You constantly hear it 

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:21.000
in the works of Chopin, Poland's greatest composer, 

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:26.000
especially when he was 

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:28.000
writing Polish nationalistic dance pieces, like 

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:31.000
Polonaises and Mazurkas. Here's a bit 

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:33.000
from one of his best-known Mazurkas; and 

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:58.000
see if you can hear that Lydian sound:

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:03.000
It's an odd sound, isn't it? So fresh and

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:05.000
sharp, like the taste of lemon-juice. And 

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:08.000
it's a very Polish sound. In fact, when 

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:11.000
the Russian composer Mussorgsky - now 

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:13.000
follow this - was writing the 

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:15.000
3rd act of 

00:29:15.000 --> 00:29:18.000
his great opera Boris Godunov -- an act which 

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:21.000
takes place in Poland -- he used this same 

00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:24.000
Lydian mode for his Polonaise, 

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:27.000
which means "Polish dance." We're going 

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:29.000
to play it for you now -- and listen for 

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:31.000
that tangy Lydian sound."

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:05.000
So far we have had a good look at 

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:08.000
three important modes - the Dorian, the 

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:11.000
Phrygian and the Lydian — those white-note 

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:13.000
scales that start on D, E, &amp; F, 

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:16.000
respectively. Now let's have a quick look 

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:19.000
at the remaining ones -- starting with the 

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:23.000
mode that begins on G and rises up

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:28.000
through the octave on the white notes 

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:31.000
This one is called (now don't panic!) — 

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:33.000
the Mixolydian mode; and 

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:37.000
despite its tongue-twisting name, it's 

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:39.000
one of the most appealing and popular 

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:41.000
modes of all. Again, like its neighbor, the 

00:33:41.000 --> 00:33:44.000
Lydian, it's a major mode, as you can hear 

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:46.000
and, like the Lydian it has one 

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:48.000
peculiar note in it, and only one - only a different one this time. 

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:50.000
See if you can 

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:54.000
tell which it is. Here is a normal G-major 

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:59.000
scale. Now here is the Mixolydian scale;

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:01.000
and I dare you to clap 

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:08.000
when you hear the one odd note. 

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:13.000
Right: it's the 7th tone, the leading tone, 

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:16.000
which is half a tone lower than 

00:34:16.000 --> 00:34:19.000
normal 

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:31.000
This is the only major mode that has 

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:34.000
a lowered leadirg tone; 

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:37.000
and believe it or not, most of the 

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:40.000
jazz and Afro-Cuban music and 

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:42.000
rock-n-roll tunes we hear owe their 

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:45.000
existence to this old Mixolydian 

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:51.000
mode. 

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:54.000
Do you hear how that lowered 7th tone 

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:57.000
makes a jazz sound?

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:57.000
Of course the examples I 

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:04.000
could give you are endless — but just to 

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:08.000
take a recent smash hit:

00:35:08.000 --> 00:35:13.000
Mixolydian. 

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:17.000
Or do you remember a terrific, 

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:20.000
barbaric song a few years 

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:24.000
ago, by The Kinks? --

00:35:44.000 --> 00:35:53.000
Pure Mixolydian. 

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:56.000
Or, take that charming Beatles tune, "Norwegian 

00:35:59.999 --> 00:36:07.000
Wood" --

00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:10.000
You hear that lowered 7th note? 

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:12.000
That makes it Mixolydian.

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:14.000
They're all 

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:16.000
Mixolydian. Now again, I don't want to 

00:36:16.000 --> 00:36:18.000
give you the idea that this mode 

00:36:18.000 --> 00:36:22.000
produces only jazz. It's 

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:24.000
still to be heard in churches as well as 

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:28.000
in discotheques. And, in fact, our old 

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:30.000
friend Debussy, when he wanted to suggest

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:33.000
a Cathedral risirg out of the sea (in 

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:35.000
his piano piece, The Sunken Cathedral) used this same 

00:36:37.000 --> 00:37:14.000
Mixolydian mode.

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:17.000
Isn't that an impressive sound.

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:19.000
And years ago, when I was 

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:27.000
writing my first ballet "Fancy Free," I 

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:31.000
too used this mode for one 

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:34.000
of the dances: and since it was a Cuban-style 

00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:37.000
dance called a danzon. I naturally 

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:40.000
used this Mixolydian mode from beginning to end; 

00:37:40.000 --> 00:37:42.000
so it ought to make a good example. Here 

00:37:42.000 --> 00:39:25.000
it is, and I hope you like it.

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:37.000
In the few minutes that remain 

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:37.000
to us, I would like to pay my brief 

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:44.000
respects to the three modes we still 

00:40:44.000 --> 00:40:46.000
haven't discussed. We can do this very 

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:48.000
quickly, as you will see, because the 

00:40:48.000 --> 00:40:51.000
first one, known as the Aeolian mode -- 

00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:55.000
which luckily starts on A, making it easy 

00:40:55.000 --> 00:40:58.000
to remember -- is almost like our normal 

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:03.000
minor scale; 

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:06.000
in fact, it is sometimes referred to as the 

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:09.000
"natural minor" mode. Its one special 

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:11.000
feature is, again, that lowered leading-tone 

00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:18.000
which makes it so similar to the Dorian 

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:19.000
and Phrygian modes that we don't even have 

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:22.000
to discuss it. Then, the next 

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:26.000
mode, starting on B, is known as the 

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:28.000
Locrian and this we can really

00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:31.000
skip, because there is almost no music 

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:35.000
written in it. The Locrian mode is 

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:38.000
strangely unsatisfying, 

00:41:38.000 --> 00:41:41.000
mainly because the 

00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:44.000
tonic chord you get from it is terribly 

00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:44.000
unsettled and inconclusive --see what I mean? So hello and 

00:41:48.000 --> 00:41:51.000
goodbye to the Locrian mode. Now we 

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:53.000
have been through all the white-note 

00:41:53.000 --> 00:41:58.000
modes, starting on D, E, F, G, A, &amp; B. And at 

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:01.000
last we come to C 

00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:04.000
the starting note of our final and most triumphant mode, 

00:42:04.000 --> 00:42:08.000
called the Ionian. Listen carefully now:

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:11.000
here is C, and up we go, white notes only,

00:42:11.000 --> 00:42:14.000
to the next C 

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:17.000
-- and what have we got? Surprise:	The C-

00:42:17.000 --> 00:42:20.000
major scale! The good old, tried and true 

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:25.000
C-major of Bach, Beethoven, Brahms, and company.

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:30.000
This major mode, once known as the 

00:42:30.000 --> 00:42:33.000
Ionian, has simply survived the evolutionary process better than 

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:36.000
all its neighbors 

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:39.000
and emerged in glory as king of 

00:42:39.000 --> 00:42:42.000
all Western music for 200 years.

00:42:42.000 --> 00:42:45.000
And so, to celebrate the king of all the modes, the major scale, 

00:42:45.000 --> 00:43:46.000
